LinkedIn Description: My biggest source of pride is hearing back from colleagues and mentees that I was somehow instrumental in their happiness and success. I genuinely enjoy influencing people to be their best (and to be kind in the process). I carve out time for mentoring and philanthropic efforts, including ones that encourage different kinds of people to pursue STEM careers. Products are always better when different perspectives contribute.The latest stop in my career is at Google, where I've been in the payments organization for over 5 years, most recently in the Payments Risk team, focused on our enterprise businesses including Cloud, Ads and Workspace. I also manage counter hijacking and federated abuse (data sharing) solutions.Our team provides fraud detection and remediation services using machine learning, rules and manual reviews - and the work never ends because fraudsters are relentless. But we're relentless, too ;-) We have made tremendous progress in helping to keep fraudulent crypto miners off the Cloud platform so that our good customers have available and reliable services. Pity the fraudsters!Previously, I managed core tokenization services for Google Pay, a mobile app that enables users to easily transact in-stores, in-app and with other users. I worked directly with the major payment networks, banks and other partners to help launch Gap brands private label cards, PayPal/Mastercard in-store support (US, Germany) and APIs for banks to deliver messages to users within Google Pay.And before that, I was a Director of Product Management in the Network and Security Business Unit (NSBU) at VMware where I managed teams and initiatives for security, automation, partnerships, APIs and user experience for NSX, the fastest growing product in VMware history.My journey to product leader is a bit unconventional. I started as an IT manager on Wall St. and also ran my own consulting firm in Silicon Valley, where I delivered go-to-market strategy/content, managed RFPs/bake-offs, and provided competitive analysis. I really think all those years as a technology customer has made me a more empathetic product manager.Lastly, my two degrees in Electrical Engineering (BS, MIT; MS, Columbia) help with technical and analytical skills but also provide healthy material for nerd jokes.
